European inflation slipped in food
The accelerating inflation in the euro area is primarily due to the rapid rise in food prices.
The price increase in November was higher than expected in all 13 euro area countries, with annual inflation of 3.1% after October's 2.6%, the Luxembourg-based Union Statistical Office announced.
Official forecasts gave only a 3 percent chance - Bloomberg announced.
The European Central Bank (ECB), unlike the US, UK and Canadian issuing banks, did not cut the basic interest rate on the pretext that the decline, together with rising commodity prices and reduced forced unemployment, would cause a spiral of inflation.
The ECB wants to keep the inflation rate below, but at least close to two percent.
According to one analyst, the ECB is in trap 22: "negotiate" on inflation so that it does not have to intervene in this issue later.
Inflation in Germany, at 3.3 percent, broke a 12-year record, while in Spain it rose from 3.6 percent to 4.1 percent.
Inflation in the euro area soared as a result of soaring food and energy prices.
The price of wheat rose by 88% and the price of soybeans reached its highest level since 1973.
Similarly, much more had to be paid in 2007 for vegetable oil and dairy products.
The price of crude oil on the world market has risen this year by 52 percent, reaching last month's black gold price of almost $100 a barrel.
According to the ECB, inflation in 2008 will jump from the current 2.1 percent to 2.5 percent, but by 2009 it will have already fallen to 1.9 percent.
According to analysts, annual inflation will remain in the next 3 or 4 months at around 3 percent, however the annual average rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, the ECB is expected to reduce interest rates twice during 2008.
Gallup predicts a government crisis
After a long stagnation, by early December support for the Young Democrats' Alliance had risen significantly, reaching its highest level since 2002, while Gallup had never before experienced such a low level - 13 percent - for the Socialists.
The difference in the case of the confident voters of the parties - due to the greater firmness of the voters of the opposition - would mean support of more than two thirds (71%) versus support of one fifth for the Socialists (20%).
The poll shows that the Democratic Forum and the Alliance of Free Democrats would not even reach the threshold necessary to have any parliamentary seat: their support within the entire population is two percent.
Among the safe voters there are one percent more sympathizers on both sides.
The economic environment continued to deteriorate even from the previous low - it has never been higher, with 41 percent of those who judged the country's economic situation particularly bad, while another 46 percent thought the situation was quite bad.
Families, after the most hopeful expectations of spring and summer, are now more pessimistic about the change in their own economic situation.
As for next year, most people expect the situation to deteriorate and only one tenth expect an improvement.
In December, 71 per cent of respondents, more than in any previous Gallup poll, felt that the Prime Minister was performing his duties more poorly than well.
13 percent of respondents trust or have a lot of confidence in Ferenc Gyurcsány, while Viktor Orbán has the support of 38 percent of respondents.
54% of the population have no confidence in the Head of Government and 27% in the president of the Alliance of Young Democrats.
One of the indicators of the political situation is how much of society thinks it is possible to control the discontent experienced with the person of the Head of Government without a change of government.
While after the October riots last year 35 percent thought it would be desirable to keep the Government and the Head of Government in power, currently this proportion is only 20 percent, while the relative majority (33 percent) believe that the only solution is to hold new elections.
Interest in the referendum is characterised by the fact that 60 percent of respondents to the question on participation said they would certainly participate and another 20 percent said they are likely to participate.
The Commission has also been asked to draw up a report on the implementation of the European Social Fund and the European Social Fund.
74 percent of the population would disapprove of paying tuition fees, 79 percent of paying for medical consultations, and 84 percent of paying for hospital care.
If we look at these proportions only among the safe participants in the referendum, 81, 84 and 89 per cent of voters would reject the introduction of education rights, payment for medical consultations and hospital care.
The most expensive is Auchan, Tesco has increased its prices fivefold
The average price level of 16 per cent was maintained by the hypermarkets in the Budaörs gold trading triangle, with the difference that no VAT increase was made this year.
Article by Napi Gazdaság
This year also the average Napi newspaper Christmas basket in the gold trading triangle of Budaörs rose by 16 percent, but all hypermarkets saw growth well above HUF 1,000.
As in December last year, food prices in supermarkets had already "shot up", so there was no dramatic percentage increase in price compared to the high starting point.
But it is obviously frightening to consumers that what they could buy last year for well under HUF 9,000 today they cannot buy for even 10,000.
The Napi basket in the hypermarkets studied exceeded the psychological limit of HUF 10,000 by a minimum of HUF 91.
And the highest-value basket was 10,573 HUF.
(In 2003 the basket cost HUF 6800.)
The price of Unicum and fish remained almost at the same level as last year, but there was a sharp increase in turkey breast fillets, walnuts and poppy seed.
The price of wheat flour and bread followed the data from the Central Statistical Office, although in Auchan we also found a kilo of bread at the price of 139 HUF.
Competition did not reduce the price of the product to less than HUF 200.
It was also surprising in this store that the price of the two-liter Coke with a redeemable bottle was less than HUF 200, so that this product, even with the price of the bottle, cost only HUF 257.
However, in Napi's basket Auchan was the most expensive, while Cora was the cheapest.
According to our calculations, with respect to last year's Christmas prices, Cora increased by 15%, while Tesco and Auchan increased by about 18% the prices listed in Napi's basket.
Comparing the values of last year's most expensive basket with this year's cheapest basket, the difference has been 12 percent, while the growth between last year's cheapest and this year's most expensive basket has been 21 percent.
The average growth was HUF 1480.
Last year the average price increase was 1206 HUF, so that during last year's Christmas the VAT increase was felt in prices.
It was this process which destroyed trade, supermarkets were visibly unable to decide on the price margin to be applied to each product and to calculate the effect of price changes on consumption.
(If the trader plans the speed of a product's circulation poorly, he may lose a significant profit on the margin that is adjusted to the volume of sales.)
The price increase of Napi basket reached such extremes as a result of the VAT increase that the most expensive one was HUF 1720 higher than the value recorded in 2006, while the cheapest one was only HUF 844.
This year there were no such extremes, as the highest price now was HUF 1630 more than last year and the cheapest also increased by HUF 1284.
Comparing the two Christmas seasons, there was a catastrophic price increase in less than 20 months, with supermarkets seeing consumer goods prices rise more than 30 percent.
(This does not necessarily confirm the figures of the Central Bureau of Statistics, however: in the case of some basic foods, this office recorded a price increase of more than 30 percent in the 12-month period.
So for example, in addition to wheat, also in the case of egg.)
According to Napi's basket, in the latter case this seems almost impossible, because the price of this product, which was quite expensive last year compared to the base, recorded, in the worst case, a mere 10 percent increase in prices.
By all indices, flour suppliers are stronger than egg suppliers and can impose the drastic price increase even on multinationals.
Hypermarkets don't complain about the golden trade triangle, they constantly talk about positive results.
In our experience, most consumers in the three stores visited are no longer interested in prices.
They buy large quantities of all products, carrying the preserved food on pallets.
On Wednesday morning, large lines formed in front of the boxes in all three stores because of the sudden increase in the number of customers.
However, we have information that in the country the sales volumes are lower, numerous multinationals complain to the survey institutes because the revenues are below their plans and not only in the case of food, but also in that of household appliances.
In many hospitals, you save money on disinfectants.
This year, several thousand infections have been recorded in hospitals, mainly due to the misuse of antibiotics.
The hygienic conditions prevailing in hospitals, the overcrowding of beds and the overload of staff do not favor the control of infections - says the head of the department of the National Center of Epidemiology.
In many hospitals, even disinfectants are saved.
Recently, an MRSA infection was diagnosed in the trauma department of the János Hospital.
A man hospitalized after a serious accident was found to have antibiotic-resistant bacteria.
The patient was isolated.
The same type of contagion occurred at this same hospital earlier this year.
A serious car accident victim was discharged from hospital and the same patient was soon to be returned to hospital as a result of MRSA and since then no major surgery has been performed because of the presence of the bacteria in his body.
As of December 10, 1094 cases of hospital infection caused by multiresistant agents have been registered in the National Nosocomialis Surveillance System - said Karolina Böröcz, medical chief of the National Center of Epidemiology.
This means that hospitals have certainly recorded this number of infections produced by multi-resistant agents, the rest are not known.
Nearly two thirds of infections (683 cases) are due to MRSA, or methicillin-oxycillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus.
One third of humans carry Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacteria in their noses without causing any disease.
Infections caused by SA (e.g. sore throat, tonsillitis, skin infections, wound infections) respond well to antibiotics and are easily treated.
However, once over- or under-applied to antibiotics, bacteria that normally react well to antibiotics turn into highly antibiotic-resistant bacteria and spread quickly in inadequate hospital conditions.
They can cause serious hospital infections, for example wound infections or sepsis, primarily in patients with transient or chronic immunodeficiency, in patients with weakened bodies, in the elderly or in people of low weight.
According to the medical director of the János Hospital, there is nothing special about MRSA infection, these infections are common in hospitals.
The infection should not be confused with the epidemic, MRSA is only absent - said Tibor Nyulasi - where its presence is not examined.
Resistant to antibiotics
"These patients are isolated, nursing staff attend to them in rubber gloves and mask and there are adequate antibiotics for their treatment", said Tibor Nyulasi.
Hospitalized patients are screened for MRSA in advance, but even this cannot prevent infection in all cases.
It's not in style to take samples.
It would be possible to prevent hospital MRSA infections in most cases, but the current national hospital circumstances do not favour the prevention of the formation and transmission of multi-resistant pathogens", says Karolina Böröcz.
Since this infection occurs mainly in hospitals and nursing homes, hospitals should screen hospitalized patients and immediately isolate patients who have MRSA in their system.
However, microbiological sampling is not in vogue in Hungarian hospitals.
This is also because the National Health Fund does not finance these medical examinations.
So most cases come to light when the MRSA infections are already visible in the patient", said the epidemiological center's chief medical officer.
The European Union makes strict recommendations for the use of antibiotics in human medicine and there are also national directives for treating infections and pathological conditions.
The aim is to ensure that antibiotic therapy is targeted, that is to say, that microbiological tests should be carried out to prevent drug resistance, but hospitals do not always meet this requirement.
Microbiological sampling is even less common in outpatients or in basic care", said Karolina Böröcz.
It saves on disinfectants
Scientific experiments have shown that in most cases MRSA is transmitted from one patient to another through healthcare workers.
The Commission has also been asked to draw up a report on the implementation of the directive on the protection of workers from the risks related to exposure to ionising radiation.
MRSA is transmitted by drop-in transmission and direct contact between people, however in national hospital circumstances it is not always possible to isolate the infected patient.
Moreover, hospital wards are often crowded, beds often very close together, although to prevent the epidemic, patients should be separated by at least 1.5 meters.
Unfortunately, it can also be experienced - Karolina Böröcz added - that in hospitals with less favourable economic situation, disinfectants are saved, there are few nurses and many patients and therefore there is a greater probability for infection.
Karolina Böröcz believes that where appropriate prevention measures are taken, fewer such infections occur or the spread of the pathogen can be stopped.
Government programme against MRSA
Treatment of MRSA is a huge expense for the National Health Insurance Fund, so it is being fought in every country.
In England, for example, there is a government program to prevent and reduce MRSA cases.
The programme appears to be successful, with MRSA infections showing a decreasing trend in England, according to the data provided.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) has among its priorities the prevention of multi-drug resistant agents (including MRSA) and hospital infections due to these pathogens.
Negative on the alcohol control for the police commander who caused a fatal accident .
The official expert report on the fatal accident caused by the commander of the police of the XXII district has been made.
It is possible that the then-dismissed commander of the police of the XXII district was driving drunk or in a daze, who on Tuesday hit and killed a passerby - reported Friday Attila Morvai, spokesman for the General Prosecutor's Office of the Capital, after having prepared the report on the case.
The expert report confirmed the result of the primary alcohol control which had already found that the former police commander had not consumed any alcoholic beverage before getting behind the wheel.
The then chief of the police station of the XXII district, on Tuesday with his private vehicle at the bend of Kossuth Lajos street of the XXII district hit a 55-year-old man, who intended to cross the street, but not in the area designated for pedestrians.
(The latter fact, that the pedestrian did not use the zebra to cross the street, according to the regulations of the Traffic Code are not mitigating circumstances, the driver must always give way when turning.)
The passerby died after being hospitalized.
The district police chief resigned and requested his retirement, according to the police statement, because he was moved by the case.
The investigation of the case is being handled by the Budapest Investigative Prosecutor's Office.
Attila Morvai also said that the former police commander from the beginning collaborated with the prosecutors in charge of the investigation.
€400 million more for infrastructure
Hungarian Finance Minister János Veres and European Investment Bank (EIB) Vice-President Marta Gajecka signed three credit agreements totalling EUR 400 million in Budapest on Friday to finance education, transport and environmental infrastructure as well as the energy sector.
The European Investment Bank (EIB) approved a budget of EUR 300 million in 2006 to finance transport and environmental protection projects in the Hungarian budget, to be carried out with a grant from the Cohesion Funds, of which the parties had previously signed a loan agreement worth EUR 100 million. The contract they have just signed concerns the use of the remaining EUR 200 million.
The EUR 150 million loan agreement is also intended to finance the budget for education projects.
The EIB has approved a total of EUR 300 million for this objective in Hungary. The decision on the use of the remaining EUR 150 million will be taken later when the loan agreement is extended.
The parties signed a €50 million contract for innovations, which the budget will mainly use for the University of Debrecen's innovation and research project.
The talks also covered the construction of the 4th Metro line.
It was agreed that by the time Hungary finalised the details of the Metro financing with the EU, they would revisit the issue of whether or not the original contract needed to be modified and how to do so.
According to János Veres, this could take place as early as the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990, the EIB has financed a total of 113 projects in Hungary worth EUR 8.4 billion.
The interest on the loans is based on the Euribor and the EIB offers an eight-year grace period, without any commission for keeping the loan available to the borrower.
Bulgaria, the real estate paradise of the EU
The development of the Bulgarian real estate market is admirable - the attention of all Europe is directed to the aforementioned Balkan country.
What, where and who is buying on the EU's even cheaper market, which will get expensive quickly?
Analysis of the Bulgarian division of Re/Max.
The preferred target for property acquisitions in Eastern Europe is undoubtedly Bulgaria, with its cheap ski slopes apartments and beach villas.
The mountainous regions of Bansko, Borovec, Pamprovo and Vitosa are the most preferred, while on the Albena beaches, the "Golden Coast", the "Sun Coast", the old Sozopol and Nesebar, but more and more people are also looking for real estate in the surroundings of Kavarna and Balchik.
According to Re/Max's analysts in Bulgaria, sooner or later the central part of the country - Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena, Triavna - will also attract real estate developers' interest and more and more people will buy properties in the especially cheap Rus area.
The capital Sofia will also be attractive, as commercial and office space promises a rapid recovery of investment.
Bulgaria is on track to become one of Europe's most attractive golfing paradises, and can thus be a major destination during the other two seasons, in addition to summer and winter.
Therefore, cautious investors are already shopping, for example in the vicinity of Bansko.
According to analysts, those who buy property in Bulgaria are also striving to change their lives and lifestyle.
Most of the customers are English, but they also come from France, Belgium, Spain and increasingly from Romania.
Maltese and Cypriot developers are also present and there are traditionally many Russian clients on the Black Sea beaches and in ski resorts.
Foreign customers can be divided into three groups - says Georgi Jankov, regional manager of Re/Max in Bulgaria.
Those who want to settle here buy new or renovated properties for a price of between 50 and 100 thousand euros or old houses in poor condition between 5 and 15 thousand euros, to renovate them later.
They require good communication and access, and they value the proximity of a large city, shops, and usually a local doctor.
The second category is comprised of villa buyers (Bulgaria was in December among the top 10 holiday destinations for Germans).
The third group is comprised of real estate investors who make their purchases in the hope of profiting in the medium to long term.
The price of capital properties is constantly rising, as demand is increasing.
Although Bulgaria has the lowest real estate prices in the European Union, over the last five years they have increased by 21 per cent a year
The increase in the price of real estate considerably outstrips the growth in wages.
Fodor and the six percent Hungarians
According to the Minister of Environment and Hidrology Gábor Fodor, the meetings at the level of experts will end on Tuesday and on Wednesday after the official inauguration will continue the negotiations at the level of ministers on the international climate regime after 2012.
Experts and policy makers from 192 countries are discussing the Bali Roadmap for post-Kyoto emissions reduction efforts through 2012.
The Commission has already made a number of proposals to this effect.
The United States has already indicated that it does not want to negotiate precise figures at the moment, although it is likely to agree to a 25 to 40 per cent reduction in greenhouse gas emissions by 2020 compared with 1990.
Another major theme of the conference is whether or not industrialized countries are willing to offer material and technological aid to countries in need, in addition to reducing emissions.
The Council also agreed on aid to developing countries.
The support fund, provided for in the Kyoto Protocol, will be managed by a 16-member steering committee, probably within the UN Global Environment Facility (GEF).
The six percent of Hungary
On behalf of Hungary, Minister for the Environment and Hydrology Gábor Fodor supports the EU's efforts to maintain its leading role in global climate protection and to promote the signing of the new international agreement by 2009.
The minister stated that the EU is committed to reducing its greenhouse gas emissions by 20 per cent by 2020 from 1990 levels, regardless of whether the 'post-2012 agreement' is signed or not, and is ready to commit to a reduction of even 30 per cent if the other major developed regions of the world and developing countries are also willing to make commitments in line with their responsibilities and capabilities.
Gábor Fodor pointed out that the signatory countries to the 1997 Kyoto Protocol committed to a 5.2 per cent reduction, of which the then 15 EU Member States committed to an 8 per cent reduction.
Hungary has committed to reducing its greenhouse gas emissions by 6 percent over the period 1985-87, which the country will meet, says the press release from the Ministry of the Environment.
There is a lot at stake in Bali, as the international agreement on long-term climate policy will have to be signed within two years, because otherwise, its entry into force will surely be postponed to after 2012. In this case, the reduction commitments, assumed in the Kyoto Protocol, would not be immediately followed by a new international system of emission reduction, the need for which was warned in its most recent report by the IPCC, the UN's international scientific association that deals with climate change, which won the Nobel Peace Prize.
This would delay the reduction of emissions and would not prevent an increase in the average temperature of the earth by more than 2°C, which scientists say would have immeasurable and irreversible consequences.
The British Army recruits on YouTube
British Army units in a video distributor publish recordings of actions filmed in Iraq and Afghanistan to popularize themselves.
The British Air Force (RAF) was the first to take advantage of YouTube services: Special forces deployed in Afghanistan since March 2006 are uploading videos of their actions against the Taliban - BBC reported.
These recordings made with mini cameras mounted on the helmets are controlled at the general operations corps in Kandahar, then sent to London to be uploaded to the Internet.
The political message is inevitable.
Already 139 recordings from the air force soldiers have been uploaded to the Internet and their "channel" has been seen by more than 75 thousand people.
The British Ministry of Defence was registered in the spring of 2007 under the name "defence headquarters" and publishes videos of both actions in Iraq and Afghanistan, while the British Commonwealth Office and the multinational forces in Iraq (MNFI) have their own YouTube channel.
Operation in Afghanistan
Originally the air force had uploaded the videos for recruitment purposes, but in the opinion of the Ministry of Defence they also serve to present to the public the true purpose of the British Army's presence abroad.
This type of propaganda costs practically nothing compared to conventional television recruitment spots - defence expert Gordon Mackenzie told the BBC - instead, it inevitably carries some political message, since it specifically justifies the rationale for military actions decided by the government.
The Americans prepared a video game
The army is also concerned that, in addition to the suspiciously edited and censored recordings, the distributor also features amateur videos, for example about the deaths of soldiers: in the "official" propaganda films, a little hypocritical, the officers talk at most of losses, without however presenting the bloody part of the fighting.
In addition, from the battlefields of Iraq and Afghanistan, numerous videos of actual operations have been uploaded to the Internet, but the British Army is only recently seizing this opportunity.
The Americans use a slightly different way of recruiting with the free-to-download shooters called America's Army, in which in the middle of a more or less real situation the player can put himself directly in the place of the soldiers.
Tombouille and salty pie at the Christmas party of the ministries
