The official nature of the event will be determined not only by the ministerial speech but also by the time of the evening.
The agriculture portfolio will offer a New Year's reception on January 20, the Ministry will not celebrate Christmas.
The reception will be held at the Vajdahunyad Castle in the Municipal Park and according to the portfolio, there will be a budget of 1000 HUF per person for the hundred guests.
This - according to the press department - will be a very simple standing reception, to which only specialised diplomats accredited in Hungary will be invited.
These annual receptions begin with a short greeting from the minister and end with a modest meal.
The Ministries of Foreign Affairs and Education and Culture will not celebrate any Christmas celebrations - this is what the relevant press departments told [origo].
The press department of the environment portfolio could not report on the budget for the Ministry's Christmas celebrations.
What is known is that more than four hundred people were invited to the party at the Museum of Applied Arts.
The giant strike is gathering forces.
The League Unions and the National Federation of Workers' Commissions will form a strike commission on Friday to coordinate the strike on Monday that will last indefinitely.
A protest rally will be held on Saturday, while a work stoppage will begin on Monday - the day of the final vote on the public health law.
This action will certainly cause great difficulties in transport, since railway traffic will be completely stopped and the workers of the Budapest Public Transport Company will also be on strike until 1 p.m.
On Friday afternoon, the League unions will report on the details of their Monday strike held jointly with the National Federation of Workers' Commissions.
The strike committee of the LIGA and the National Machinists' Union will also be formed to coordinate the actions on Monday.
On Saturday a protest rally will be held, while on Monday the participating unions will go on strike indefinitely, if no agreement is reached with the government.
This means that - on the day of the parliamentary vote on the public health law - they did not inform about the date of the end of the strike started.
If the National Assembly disapproves of the public health law, the unions will immediately withdraw their call for a strike.
If the law is passed, the strike committees will meet and decide on the future.
Based on the agenda of Monday's National Assembly it is also possible that the public health law will only be voted on in the late hours of the night, or perhaps near midnight.
The strike on Monday will cause significant difficulties in transport: railways will be closed indefinitely, part of Budapest's public transport may be stopped in the morning and more than half of Volan's intercity bus services may be stopped.
At the same time, in many parts of the country, half of the roads will be closed.
Numerous unions and civil organizations have joined the strike, their names constantly updated on the League's website.
Some unions announced their strike for an indefinite time, others for a definite time.
Until Thursday afternoon, the State Railways and the Free Union of Railway Workers (SLTF) could not reach an agreement even on the minimum services, although, as the Christmas holidays approach, more and more people are traveling in trains.
According to information received so far, from the beginning of the day until 13 hours will be on strike the workers of the Empresa de Transporte Colectivo de Budapest, the Budapest Airports from 7 to 9 in the morning, will hold a four-hour strike the LIGA Unions of the Electric Industry and Thermal Energy, the Educators' Unions called a strike of 2 and the Democratic Union of Educators from 2 to 8 hours.
The Hungarian Association of Doctors will go on a nationwide strike at alternative times and the Democratic Union of Workers in the Health and Social Sector (SDTSSS) which are part of the Trade Union Cooperation Forum, will hold a two-hour warning strike.
The most important of the four demands made by the League is that the government withdraw its proposal for public health reform and submit a new conception to a social debate.
The second demand is that the new pension calculation system, which will come into force next year, be introduced gradually.
The third is to ensure that, even before 2010, the occupations which deserve early retirement are able to enter the system.
The fourth reason for the strike is that the Free Union of Railway Workers (SLTF) which is part of the League Unions, does not accept the proposal of the Ministry of Economy and Transport on the railway side lines and is waiting for another proposal.
Political Capital[b1]: In the country the risk is increased by the Hungarian Guard
According to the Risk Analysis Division of Political Capital, the activity of the Hungarian Guard, which was set up in August this year with the support of the Movement for a Better Hungary, has in various ways increased the political risk of Hungary and the region.
The company's 'risk warning' states: 'The biggest political risk in relation to the Hungarian Guard's activity is the fact that 'with the worsening of ethnic tensions between the Roma and non-Gypsy population in Hungary, violent ethnic clashes may occur even in the short term'.
The main reason for this is that the political strategy of the Hungarian Guard is probably to provoke an event of this nature - added the representative of the research institute.
They claimed that this was due to one of the main faults of the Hungarian political actors: 'the public actors gave the public debate on the Roma problem to the representatives of radical and extremist political groups, who could base their political strategy on the existing differences between Roma and Hungarians'.
This aggravates the problem, makes normal dialogue impossible, strengthens extremists and increases the likelihood of violent conflicts breaking out - they estimate.
In addition, according to the research institute, the activity of the National Guard, as a result of the great attention of the national and international media, "significantly deteriorated the image of Hungary abroad, especially as regards the stability and democratic development of the country".
We are reminded that: from autumn 2006 onwards, the reorganisation of the radical and far-right groups in Hungary received increasing publicity and impetus and that since the summer of 2007 numerous organisations have been established in the country which call themselves 'national self-defence associations'.
"The common feature of these groups is that they define themselves as civil organizations, while they openly proclaim the training of their members for defense - even armed - (civil defense, national defense, defense of public order), alluding to the ineptitudes of the police, the army, that is, the State" - they add.
They claimed: all this is done in accordance with the method which attempts to give a civil presentation to different political aspirations, based on society's discontent with politics and political parties.
The Commission has already taken a number of steps to ensure that the legal framework for the registration of associations is not changed.
According to the analysis, the activity of the Hungarian Guard is also a risk factor from the point of view of neighbourly relations.
"In recent months, in many neighbouring states the Hungarian Guard was referred to as a potential danger, while ultra-nationalist political figures in certain neighbouring countries, want to justify their own anti-Hungarian policy by the creation of the Hungarian Guard.
All this has an influence on the political stability of the region", they added.
According to the research institute, the establishment of the Hungarian Guard is not an isolated phenomenon in Central and Eastern Europe, so political risks increased throughout the region.
They wrote that the Hungarian Guard functions in a similar way to, for example, the Bulgarian National Guard, whose constitution was announced in August 2007 by the far-right Bulgarian National Union (UNB).
The establishment of the Bulgarian Guard is due to the massive Roma riots that occurred in one of the Sofia neighborhoods (Krasna Poliana).
Taking advantage of this situation, the UNB decided to constitute the guard, arguing that the organization's objective is "national self-defense".
In his opinion, in the last 17 years there was "gypsy terror" in Bulgaria, however the State remained impotent and indifferent to the facts - recalls the Political Capital.
