The party isn't always written in red numbers.
In Hungary the law defines precisely the days which are written in red numbers on the calendar and it has already become a widespread practice that around the holidays - which will be fewer next year - the working days are reorganized.
Even in the EU or North America, holidays are not uniform.
Hungarian law makes a distinction between national holidays, state holidays and public holidays.
The holidays are mainly related to religious and historical holidays.
We celebrate the New Year too: both the last day of the old year and the first day of the new year are holidays - the latter especially so that those who spent celebrating the old year can rest.
Throughout the year we have eleven holidays written in red numbers on the calendar.
It is a national holiday on 15 March in memory of the 1848 revolution and on 23 October, commemorative day of the 1956 revolution.
On 20 August we celebrate the foundation of the State, on 1 May the Labor Day, on 1 and 2 November we remember our deceased relatives and friends.
In addition, Easter, Pentecost, and Christmas are two-day festivals in our country.
According to the calendar, our state, national or religious holidays rarely coincide with a weekend, so often a bridge is made when before or after the holiday there is only one working day.
In exchange for the extended weekends, you cannot miss work or school on the Saturdays before.
The Minister of Labour makes a specific decree on when work must be done in exchange for the day immediately preceding or following the holiday.
This legal provision is binding on all employers and their employees, as well as on employees and public officials.
It is not compulsory for companies and service institutions which, because of their function, work continuously even during public holidays.
This year the work order will be altered only around the end of the year holidays: from 24 December onwards, life in the country will almost stop, as according to experience, most people "bridge" during the days between Christmas and the end of the year or take their holidays during these days.
Next year, many of our holidays will fall on a midweek or weekend, so there will be fewer changes in working days than this year.
First, the agenda will be changed around Labor Day so that workers can rest for four consecutive days.
Saturday, April 26 will be a working day, so that Friday, May 2 will be a holiday.
The other change is related to the holiday of 23 October: on Saturday 18 October, you will have to work instead of Friday 24.
The next year, however, the holiday will be a rest day, since from 24 December onwards almost no work will be done, even if the last day of the year is a Wednesday.
Six little dissuasive measures to make your colleagues' lives miserable.
E-mails we forget to send, voicemails we never get, innocent lies that pass us by without us even realizing it: all of these are part of our "everyday workplace folklore".
You have to decide whether you will accommodate minor annoyances or consciously avoid confusing situations that may irritate others.
I'll give you some advice.
"Sorry, I forgot to tell you that you've been contacted by the marketing department", says one of your colleagues".
That's why you didn't go on a date?
At best, he feels sorry and tries to fix the problem, perhaps calling the marketing department to tell them that he forgot to deliver the message (this is the less common solution).
Most of the time, the issue is resolved with an apology.
Before proceeding with embarrassing explanations, it is worthwhile to meditate on the things you can do to make your colleagues' lives bitter and to make a conscious effort to avoid them.
You borrow something that's not yours?
There's nothing more irritating than when you want to grab a document, an office supply or your phone and you can't find them.
Do you remember yesterday you put the stapler on the table, but by this morning it was gone?
Did you find your pen lost on the desk of one of your colleagues?
Don't take anything from your colleagues without asking them, because they'll be rightly angry with you for stealing their stuff.
Don't pick up envelopes or post-its from the office because it may be unpleasant when you need them immediately and they sell out before their time.
You gossip about your colleagues' private lives?
There's no good solution to stop rumors that are already circulating.
Who, what is he doing and with whom?
Where and why?
Don't pass on to everyone the information (guesses) you have about your colleagues' private lives!
Don't abuse your colleague's trust when he shares his innermost secrets with you!
Keep what you have heard to yourself, and do not gossip about your colleague in his absence, even if others know his things.
You're taking sick leave unjustifiably?
When you call the office and say you are sick and have excruciating headaches, you feel sick or otherwise, you feel that you would rather rest that day; think that others should do your work, your unreserved tasks, your work by the deadline.
Don't bother your colleague!
If you know in advance that you will not be at work the next day or that something may happen to you, and you must stay at home, let them know so that your colleagues or your boss do not have to face your absence the next day.
Barking, laughing, phone calls
Are you busy with your work, but suddenly your colleagues laugh at you?
Have you ever unintentionally overheard a phone conversation that you should have just ignored?
Don't bother your colleagues with your humming, singing, loud conversations (less when you're doing them over their head), kicking, constant blasphemy, expressing your discontent out loud.
All of these can be annoying, even if you are not currently delving into a project (writing, planning, organizing).
Do you blame others for a mistake?
Don't blame others if you didn't finish something on time, forgot to send an important letter or message!
You don't mention the chaos that may eventually reign in the office, or the noise your colleagues make!
You must acknowledge if you have made a mistake that hurts others and you must make amends!
Ask how you can make up for your mistake!
Do you feel too at home in the office?
Jogging and sneakers: very comfortable habit for the house, but not suitable for the office!
Don't wear a comfortable jogging suit even if your occupation allows it!
Don't be disorganized, respect your colleagues and yourself by wearing everyday, elegant and beautiful clothes when your occupation demands it!
