The banks want to solve the crisis
The US Federal Reserve, the European Central Bank and the British, Swiss and Canadian central banks decided to fight together against the financial market crisis.
The monetary market will receive more than a hundred billion dollars through tendering.
In these tenders banks auction off the interest rates at which they are able to lend money.
For example, the American Fed will send forty billion dollars to bid, and then another twenty-four billion will be provided by the central banks of Europe and Switzerland.
After the attacks of 9/11, it is the first time that central banks from different states have agreed on this coordinated process to protect and mitigate the consequences of the financial crisis.
"This step should solve the biggest economic problem, namely the continuing growth of the shortage of free capital that banks could lend", wrote Bernard Baumohl of the consulting firm Economic Outlook Group in his report to clients.
"This coordinated action by central banks probably reduced the recession in the United States from 65 percent to 50 percent", Baumohl added in his report.
Banks have already spent $60 billion on unpaid loans, mostly in the United States.
Economists still expect billions in losses.
"Central banks should be really afraid of what awaits them even when they decided to take this step", said ABN Amro's chief economist Kieran Davies.
"It seems that the situation is really bad", he added.
Central banks fear that they will have the same problems accessing loans and will therefore have to lend more expensive to their customers.
This would reduce consumption and send the American economy into recession with different impacts on the growth of the world economy.
The central banks decided to do so after failing to reduce the so-called LIBOR rate, the London interbank rate used for lending money in the interbank market.
This means that banks were constantly afraid to lend money even when the central banks of the US, Canada and Britain cut their interest rates several times during the autumn.
"It will have the same effect as another fall in interest rates", Greg Salvaggio of Tempus Consulting told Reuters.
Some economists are not surprised that the move by central banks is contributing to the crisis because it does not solve the fundamental problem of the collapse of the US housing market.
