A spectacular repair on the space station
It must have taken astronaut Scott Parazynski and his crewmates on the International Space Station (ISS) more than seven hours of space work to perform the spectacular repair of a torn solar panel that is vital to the station's continued scientific activities.
A risky departure that set records for its duration, its distance from the habitable modules, the speed with which it was imagined, instruments "snatched" by the astronauts to make the repair.
The problem arose on Tuesday when astronauts released the Harmony module from the Discovery spacecraft, a cylindrical, thick piece of equipment that will soon house European and Japanese scientific laboratories (see box).
This module is a type of landing platform for the lab-modules.
But you have to be able to supply them with electricity.
The second task of the crew was to move a 17.5-ton solar-powered power generation module already on the ISS to its final position.
After moving it, the crew began rearranging the module's 76-meter-wide solar panels.
And that's where one of the panels, which unfolds like accordions, has been damaged by a cable that got stuck in about a meter.
The deployment has been stopped to prevent further damage to the panel.
The astronauts, who were originally to take a control exit from the shuttle Discovery, and then go to repair another solar panel whose rotation system was defective, were forced to devote themselves to the damaged panel.
And it is Scott Parazynski who has been chosen to go snorkeling at the end of the 100-foot long shuttle's remote control arm added to the station's to perform repairs.
He's one of the best spacewalkers at NASA.
Tall, tough, very skilled, with a well-developed torso and long arms.
At the age of 46, this trained doctor has been tasked with "operating" the "wounded" solar panel.
After inspecting the damage precisely, he cut the faulty cable and installed "tablet" types in the damaged area.
He had been helped by a second spacewalker who had stayed near the airlock and, from inside, by other astronauts such as Peggy Whitson, the crew commander.
The tool he used, a mini hockey stick wrapped in insulation to prevent electrocution in solar panels that produced several hundred volts, has been conceived and "chopped" by the astronauts aboard the station.
Once the operation was over, Scott Parazynski waited for the panel to be fully deployed before taking inventory of his instruments and returning to the station.
Yesterday afternoon, the astronauts took advantage of a lunch break before today, seven astronauts return from the shuttle Discovery for the scheduled return to Earth on Wednesday.
