The choice of the status quo
No surprise on Sunday, at the polls: Russians are going to vote massively for President Putin's party, United Russia.
Confirming his aspiration for stability, even authoritarianism, after a very limited campaign.
Three days before the parliamentary elections, Russian President Vladimir Putin addresses the electorate today with a televised message on public television channels, already recorded but whose content is kept secret.
He does so as the leader of the list for United Russia, the pro-Kremlin party whose victory turns out to be crushing.
Yesterday, the president let nothing get out of hand by hosting foreign ambassadors, content to hand over a new charge against the West accused of interference - his favorite topic during the campaign.
"We know the price of true democracy and we want honest, more transparent and more open elections, elections without incidents", he added.
According to the opposition, we are far from the truth.
He denounces a campaign tainted by pressure.
Communist leader Gennady Ziouganov says there have never been "so dirty elections, even in the time of Yeltsin".
After the crackdown on demonstrations last weekend, former world chess champion Garry Kasparov, sentenced to five days in prison for an illegal demonstration, is banned from visiting, according to his lawyer.
"The Russians kept the mentality of the homo Soviet"
Behind these unexpected legislative elections are two much more open questions:
Who will succeed Putin as president?
The official newspaper published yesterday the date of the first round of the presidential election, March 2, 2008; the candidates have until December 23 to make themselves known.
Elected in 2000 and re-elected in 2004, Vladimir Putin cannot seek a third consecutive term.
Then no successor emerges.
What role will Putin play after March?
Prime Minister?
Leader of the parliamentary majority and the very powerful United Russia party that would elect the government and the president?
Whatever happens, in the legislative elections as in the presidential elections, the outgoing power will triumph.
It's a tradition.
"The Russians have retained the mentality of homo sovieticus, they do not feel they own their destiny", says sociologist Lev Goudkov, director of the independent Levada Center.
Historian Nikolaï Kopossov of St. Petersburg State University goes further: civil society in this Christianized country fell behind Europe by five centuries; the famous community spirit delayed the formation of individualism.
After the liberal reforms of the 1990s, "Putin re-established the model of a paternalistic state, perfectly accepted by the population since this new paternalism has not been followed by terrorism, but by a certain economic release", estimates Maria Lipman of the Carnegie Foundation.
Today the Russians "voluntarily renounce personal responsibility" for those who had briefly been tested after the USSR's collapse.
"Why reflect?"
The phenomenon affects all social strata, including the business world.
And the administrative elite thinks to preserve the status quo: 65 governors (out of every 85 heads of Russian regions) run the local lists of united Russia.
New freedoms imported from the West are often synonymous with chaos, as in the 1990s.
Opinion prefers stability.
In the name of the Russians not voting for extremists either.
Conclusion of Tamara Tcherednitchenko, 54-year-old teacher: "Why reflect?
Those in power are not so bad, why change them?"
A heavy memory
After more than 60 years of confidentiality, the Bad Arolsen Nazi archives, which describe the fate of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are now open to the public.
The 47 million archival documents, stored on 27 km of shelves in Bad Arolsen (Hesse), were not hitherto accessible only for 'humanitarian' purposes, i.e. individually and nominally, at the request of a former victim or his beneficiaries.
The eleven states responsible for managing them - including Germany, France, Israel and the United States - agreed in May 2006 to open them to researchers and historians.
The process of ratification of this agreement by all States has been completed, and the opening took effect yesterday.
The information shall be kept confidential.
Historians' access to Bad Arolsen will allow for searches "particularly on the movements of prisoners, the camp population and the health status of forced labourers", explains Reto Meistern, director of the archives managed by the International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC).
Until recently, several States, such as Germany, were opposed to the opening of these nominative documents to the public, because of the sensitive nature of certain information.
As well as the alleged homosexuality or mental disability of certain deportation victims.
Records of concentration camps or arrest warrants issued by the Gestapo had been compiled after the war for a practical purpose: to find the peasants deported or forced to work and, if necessary, to provide them with proof of their internment, in order to pave the way for their compensation.
Even today in Bad Arolsen, more than 300 permanent employees handle tens of thousands of individual claims.
However, access to Bad Arolsen is of limited interest to a part of the scientific community.
"There is nothing fundamentally new to expect from these documents", said Professor Wolfgang Benz, director of the Research Center on Antisemitism at the Technische Universität Berlin in 2006.
