The Congress approves the transposition of MiFID, which entered into force on 1 November.
In parallel to the parliamentary process, which ended today with the vote by the Congress on the amendments to the bill in the Senate, the Government has submitted to public hearing the regulation that will develop the new law, with the aim of both coming into force before the end of the year.
The representatives of the different groups agreed to highlight the efforts made by Members of Parliament and Senators to negotiate and agree on the best regulations to ensure investor protection and to regulate the activity of entities in detail so that markets function efficiently.
The MiFID, which amends the Securities Market Act, aims to modernise financial markets while strengthening investor protection, improving the supervisory powers of the National Securities Market Commission (CNMV) and promoting cooperation between the various supervisors in the European Union.
The new rules will allow financial advisory services to be provided to both specialist firms and natural or legal persons and create a new type of financial services firm (FSI), financial advisory firms (FAs), which join securities firms, stockbrokers and portfolio management companies.
It also extends the number of systems for the execution of transactions in financial instruments, so that regulated secondary markets are joined by multilateral trading systems and order internalisation systems, which will compete with current stockbrokers.
The law also requires investment firms to disclose on the market information on key aspects of their business profile, risk exposure and risk management and requires them to keep a record of all transactions they carry out, to facilitate supervision by the CNMV.
In its passage through the Committee on Economics of the Congress, several modifications were incorporated, among which it highlights that securitised debts are considered a "complex" financial instrument given their high risk for the investor, which has been demonstrated with the debt of high-risk US mortgages (subprime).
In addition, the transposition of the directive was used to legally delimit the functions that graduates in economics and business can perform 30 years after the Royal Decree delimiting the professional functions reserved for economists was adopted in 1977.
The Senate, for its part, has incorporated the creation of new figures in the financial sector, such as the mediator, who will work for a third party, will not require authorisation from the CNMV and will be able to provide services for marketing products and attracting clients to different investment companies at the same time.
