This was announced at a press conference by the PSOE's secretary of organisation, José Blanco, and Bono himself, after the meeting he held this afternoon at the party's federal headquarters with Zapatero.
The head of the Executive has justified the offer to the former minister because "it is important to have the best" in political life and Bono "is among the best".
He also pointed out that "it seems" that the manchego politician will be the candidate of the socialist group to preside over the Congress if the socialists win in the next elections.
Bono would replace Manuel Marín as Congress president, who made public on November 15 his decision not to stand in the next general election and to abandon his career in active politics to devote himself to fighting climate change in the university field.
The former minister has acknowledged that the government president has not stopped insisting that he return to the political vanguard since he left it two years ago.
He also pointed out that, just as citizens know who will be the economic vice president if the PSOE wins the elections, his party has wanted to announce who will preside over the Congress, in an "act of transparency".
If he takes office, Bono hopes to turn the House into "the house of respect and not of insult or scream". and make it "more and more like citizens".
"Sometimes it seems unfortunate that the only place in Madrid where one cannot speak with tranquility and tranquility is the Congress, the President of the Government was interrupted in the Senate 26 times".
He also praised his current president, Manuel Marín, for his "good work" and did not want to see himself occupying his position to avoid falling into what he said his opponents might see as "prepotence".
Propaganda on the climate
As the climate change movement mercilessly persecutes both skeptics of its predictions and those who prioritize other political and social battles, it is forced to show iron coherence.
And a leader of the movement who is president of the government like Zapatero and believes that this fight is more important than that of Islamist terrorism and even proposes to sign a "new contract with the planet".
This approach obliges him to explain why the action, or inaction, of his government has contributed decisively to Spain leading the EU in non-compliance with Kyoto.
Who is responsible for the breach, in which sectors it has occurred and why your government, the one with the planet contract, has not prevented it.
It also requires him to explain as clearly as possible to the Spanish people what measures he will take to curb climate change.
What businesses will be affected, what habits of citizens will have to be changed, what individual and collective energy savings we will be forced to make, what economic consequences will it have.
I mean, who will sacrifice and who will pay to save the planet.
But there have been no such explanations.
Precisely because it's about sacrifice and paying.
Measures against climate change, real measures, are unpopular.
Costly, inconvenient and threatening to corporate and individual accounts.
Even the penny of petrol suggested by the PSOE has seemed so dangerous to Zapatero that he has rushed to deny it.
So it's about saving the planet with nothing, with pure propaganda, with empty slogans with no real consequences.
With shocking phrases, commissions, committees, protocols, new charges.
