New fears over gas between Russia and Ukraine
The growing dispute over the price of gas between Ukraine and Russia increases the risk that it will affect Russia's fuel exports to Western Europe.
Most of Russia's gas exports to the European Union (EU) are routed through Ukraine, so every touch between the two nations is a source of attention.
Kiev has warned that if Moscow raises gas prices, Russia will have to pay higher transit fees.
An earlier dispute last year reduced supplies to EU states.
The latest dispute between Kiev and Moscow came with the Ukrainian government and the Russian state, monopoly gas owner Gazprom, trying to agree on how much money Ukraine should pay for Russian gas in 2008.
Gazprom said it would charge Ukraine more, as it has committed to paying an extra 50% in 2008 for gas coming from neighboring Turkmenistan.
Analysts say it could be that Ukraine pays 40% more for Gazprom imports.
"It is important for us to use our arguments as one of the most important transit routes for gas during the talks", Ukrainian Economy Minister Anatoly Kinakh told Reuters news agency.
"Changes in gas prices should not relate to our arguments about the levels of transit fees [to Western Europe] via Ukraine".
In the last major gas dispute between Moscow and Kiev, Gazprom cut off supplies to Ukraine in January 2006.
This meant a drop in exports to Western Europe, which quickly drove up prices.
Russian gas accounts for a quarter of the EU's supply.
Russia has the world's largest gas reserves, but much of it is still not fully developed.
As a result, Gazprom supplements its own gas supplies with Turkmenistan and other former Soviet nations in Central Asia.
"the NHS will have to test foreign workers"
The Scottish NHS needs to check the criminal records of employees from outside Europe, a watchdog said.
Auditor General Robert Black's recommendation came after it was found that a foreign doctor was linked to the Glasgow airport attack in June.
Black also expressed concern that the Scottish NHS has no exact idea how many foreign staff it has.
However, their report pointed to other checks being carried out correctly through a sample of five health authorities.
The Auditor-General checked the number of foreign staff hired outside the European Economic Area following the attacks at Glasgow airport.
Bilal Abdullah, 28, an Iraqi doctor from the Royal Alexandra Hospital in Paisley, was arrested at the airport after crashing a jeep into the gates of the airport terminal building.
He was one of three doctors who performed at the Old Bailey by video conference in October, charged in connection with the alleged car bombings in the UK.
NHS expects to carry out pre-employment checks on candidates, to ensure they meet qualifications, experience and authorisation to work in the UK.
Although the Scottish Health Board uses Disclosure Scotland to carry out criminal background checks, the agency has no jurisdiction to obtain this information outside Great Britain.
The auditor general's report recommends, among other measures, that boards should have the guidance of the Criminal Records Bureau, which helps employers with criminal checks in many countries outside Britain.
"Although we found some of the personal records with evidence of these checks, this is not a routine review", the report says.
Black states that the Scottish NHS has a high level of compliance with its own employment policies, but notes that: 'our report highlights areas where improvements can be made to ensure that the necessary information is available on the number of foreign NHS staff.'
BMA Scotland president Dr Peter Terry said it was "very unlikely" that pre-employment checks could identify potential NHS employees who might commit terrorist acts in the future.
"The report suggests that pre-employment checks work in NHS Scotland but it is not clear what the added value of the recommendations made is", he explained.
The Scottish health authorities say they currently have 1,161 foreigners, most of them doctors and nurses.
But the auditor general warned that the number may be higher, in part because boards have trouble identifying which employees have indefinite residency permits.
The investigation also found that the screening procedures set by NHS authorities in Ayrshire and Arran, Grampian, Greater Glasgow and Clyde, Lanarkshire and Lothian were being broadly followed.
This includes passport checks, work permits and qualifications checks.
The Scottish Government is currently reviewing the policy and guidance on pre-employment of foreigners in the NHS.
Health Secretary Nicola Sturgeon said: "There was a strong interest in this work being carried out in the wake of the Glasgow airport terrorist attack.
He added that the Scottish Government, together with the health boards, could consider the recommendations of the reports and that this would be reflected in the updating of the pre-employment control guidelines for all work groups - including foreigners - which they were planning to publish next month.
Joy Division dominates the film awards
Control, the biographical film about the late Joy Division frontman Ian Curtis, has won five awards at the British Independent Film Festival, including the Best Film award.
The trophies were also given to lead actor Sam Riley, who worked in a warehouse until he was cast as Curtis, to director Anton Corbijn and co-star Toby Kebbell.
Actress Judi Dench was named best actress for the thriller "Notes from a Scandal".
And the Bond star, Daniel Craig, won the Variety Award for putting a British film on the international stage.
The awards were presented at a ceremony at the Roundhouse in London.
Control follows Curtis' rise to fame with Joy Division, until his suicide in 1980, at the age of 23.
The film - in black and white - featuring soundtracks by The Killers, David Bowie and New Order - was produced for just £3,000.
But also the winner was Dutch photographer Corbijn, already known for the iconic cover of U2's Joshua Tree album, awarded two awards - best director and best debut director.
Rock music was the focus of another award winner at the ceremony - like Julien Temple's film about The Clash vocalist Joe Strummer, won the award for best documentary.
The Best Actor award went to Viggo Mortensen for his role as the chauffeur of a Russian mafia boss in David Cronenberg's film Promises from the East.
Ray Winstone, who has a reputation for playing hardball, received the Richard Jarris Award for his contribution to British cinema.
The 50-year-old, whose films include Scum, Nil By Mouth and Sexy Beast, is currently filming the Indiana Jones sequel "The Kingdom of the Crystal Skull".
Winstone said he was proud to receive the award, named after Harry Potter and Camelot star Harris, who died in 2002.
"It was people like Richard Harris and Albert Finney who opened doors to people like me", he said.
"I was lucky enough to meet Richard Harris a couple of times.
He was a great guy, a great actor of our time, it's really an honor".
The Independent Film Awards, known as BIFAS, are selected by a team that includes filmmakers, actors and festival organizers.
Supporters and patrons of the Bifa festival include Mike Figgis, Ken Loach, Ewan McGregor, Samantha Morton, Bill Nighy, Meera Syal and Michael Winterbottom.
Saudi Arabia arrests 208 terrorists
Saudi Arabia revealed yesterday that it has arrested 208 militants from terrorist cells who were planning an imminent attack on oil facilities, as well as attacks on religious and security forces.
State television from the world's largest oil supplier said one of the cells was planning to smuggle missiles.
Al-Qaeda sympathizers have mounted a campaign against the local monarchy, in alliance with the United States, since 2003 after the invasion of Iraq.
An eight-member cell of foreign residents was planning an attack on an oil facility in the Eastern Province, the television report said.
Saudi Arabia created a 35,000-strong force to protect the facilities of Abqaiq, the world's largest oil refinery, after a failed Al-Qaeda attack in 2006.
The report, citing a statement from the Saudi Interior Ministry, said 18 of the arrested belong to a cell led by a "missile launch expert", who has entered the country.
The minister said the militants had planned to smuggle eight projectiles into the country.
Another 22 of the detainees were planning assassinations of religious leaders and security forces.
The government warned religious leaders that they must be more active in stopping Saudis traveling to Iraq from joining as al-Qaeda militants to fight allied forces and supporting the Shiite Muslim government, which is considered heretical by the most extreme Sunni Saudis.
Al-Qaeda militants have targeted many clerics in Saudi Arabia who have been designated by the authorities to support the policies of the royal family, which dominates the government.
The militants - recruited by calls from Osama Bin Laden, the Saudi-born leader of Al Qaeda, to harass the country's pro-Western government - targeted residences of foreigners associated with the government, government buildings and energy facilities.
"This was a great effort by the security forces, five months of work", the interior minister's spokesman told state television.
The arrests also include a 16-person "media cell" in Medina, whose aim was to promote "takfiri thinking" - the ideology of radical Sunni Muslims that supports violence against Muslims deemed infidels and apostates.
The arrest includes 32 other people accused of providing support and financial support to the militants.
Venus' climate may give us a glimpse into Earth's future
Venus may have once been a suitable place for life, scientists said yesterday.
Data from a European spacecraft in orbit showed the planet more like an Earth twin than had been previously observed.
Venus is the closest planet to Earth.
The two planets are similar in size and orbit, although Venus is slightly closer to the sun.
Millions of years ago, Venus may have had conditions similar to those that made Earth a habitable planet, scientists now believe.
But the effects of carbon dioxide and the greenhouse effect, the atmospheric erosion from solar radiation and the slower solar rotation sent Venus into a very different kind of development.
Today the planet has no water, the surface temperature is high enough to melt lead, and it is eroded by hurricane winds and lightning storms.
The results of the European Space Agency's Venus Express, which has studied the planet for a year, offer a glimpse of how Earth could develop catastrophic changes because of climate.
Professor Fred Taylor, of the Department of Physics at Oxford University and one of the leaders of the Venus Express mission, states: "It is becoming clear why the climate on Venus is so different from Earth, when they are two planets so similar.
"Our new data make it possible to construct a scenario in which Venus began as Earth, possibly with a habitable environment millions of years ago".
