A trio of retired generals started a riot in the House of Lords, protesting cuts in military spending: being ministers of the armed forces is, they claimed, a part-time job.
Now it's the multiple donations of David Abrahams; Peter Watt, the Labour general secretary (and former accomplice) has already resigned.
None of this means Mr. Brown is walking irrevocably to the exit.
Governments can reach a tipping point after they find themselves unable to govern.
People don't believe them as politicians, but they usually suspend their disbelief when a new batch takes over.
Once it is clear that the prime minister cannot improve things, that he has little time left, that suspension is too much: public officials start to fail; cabinet ministers expose themselves; the press looks for bad news; and the government becomes defensive and does not focus.
On the one hand, Brown's position is particularly difficult, because unlike other political leaders he cannot defend himself by arguing that he is new.
As much as I'd like to disown Tony Blair, he was his senior lieutenant.
The problems of Northern Rock and the authority registration tax are related to the decisions Brown made as chancellor of the exchequer.
And even though he's not directly involved in the Blairish mishaps - or "cash for partners", the investigation into political party funding - voters can assume he is.
However, Mr. Brown's situation is not as bad as it seems.
The plates aren't as bad as the Tories want to make them look.
Like Mr. Bean, no one's been killed or ripped off directly.
And the remedy, though painful, is to give what Mr. Brown's naturally Stalinist tendencies have always promised: a reliable and brutal government.
The new political donation scandal is a good example.
Mr. Abrahams, who compares his donations to charitable gifts, says he does not want public recognition for his benevolence.
This may be so, but the decision is not his.
The laws against anonymity for big political contributors are clear and there's a clear reason: the public has a right to know who's buying access to those in power.
Mr. Watt, who said he knew about Mr. Abraham's deal, and that it wasn't illegal, will obviously be facing Jon Mendlesohn, the fundraising manager who was asked about the donations in October.
But Mr. Brown is so far not involved: there is nothing to suggest that he knew of these performances, although the bulk of the payments were made after he took control of the office in June.
So far the Prime Minister has done half the work.
He has been quick to condemn his party for breaking the law, but he's diluted in decision-making over a family matter, a commission of inquiry into the matter - led, to a large extent, by a judge and a bishop.
In this case, the morals are not complicated.
If the law has been broken, it's a police matter.
In addition, there are other things Mr Brown must do, such as finding a permanent and independent head for the Standards Committee on Public Life, since he has not had one for six months, and he must also push for genuine reform of party funding.
This will require hard co-operative work by Labour with the Tories, and perhaps a waiver of the special financial status that is enjoyed by the unions - bitter measures for a partisan like Mr Brown.
But he has to face some partisan facts.
The Conservatives now have a good level of support in the polls; he has two years to win voters; and the only way he can move to victory is by acting with impeccable probity and solid competition.
Card sharks
Is the subprime mortgage crisis infecting the American credit card market?
When there's blood in the water, it's natural for some dorsal fins to swim excitedly around.
Today, as the American housing market is in crisis, predators have their sights set on the country's credit card market.
Analysts at Goldman Sachs estimate that credit card losses could reach $99 million if the subprime mortgage crisis spreads to other forms of consumer credit.
Signs of infection are already showing.
There is an increase in both card charges and crime rates, which measures the proportion of balances that have not been repaid or are more than 30 days late, respectively.
HSBC announced last month that it has taken $1.4 million in its American consumer finance business, in part due to weakness of card borrowers.
It's too early for panic, though.
Late payments and crime are at low levels.
According to Moody's, a rating agency, the third quarter crime rate of 3.89 percent was almost one percentage point below the historical average.
The deterioration in rates can be partly explained by technical factors.
A change in the American bankruptcy law of individuals (2005) resulted in a sharp drop in bankruptcy filings, which in turn represented a large loss on credit cards; the number of filings (and therefore, delinquency) would be growing again, or it may happen that conditions for borrowers were worsening.
The industry also reports solid payment rates, which show how much of its debts consumers pay off each month.
And confidence in credit cards and asset-backed securities is pretty solid, despite the paralysis in other financial areas.
Dennis Moroney of TowerGroup, a research firm, predicts that emissions volumes for 2007 will be about 25% higher than last year.
The direct channels of crisis infection between subprime mortgages and the credit card market certainly exist: consumers like to load debts onto credit cards now that credit institutions are expiring.
But credit card issuers look more at the flow of liquidity than at assets, so falling prices do not necessarily trigger a change in borrowers' creditworthiness.
They can even work to out-compete the issuers.
The incentives for consumers to keep paying off the mortgage decrease if the property is worth less than the loan value, and as a result, paying off the card debt rises to the top of the list of priorities.
Card issuers can also respond quickly and flexibly to difficult conditions than mortgage lenders, by changing interest rates or altering creditors' balances.
That should theoretically reduce the risk of a rapid asset reassessment.
"We're not going to wake up one day and reassess all the loans", says Gary Perlin, chief financial officer at Capital One.
If a sudden subprime infection in the credit card market is unlikely, the risks of a sustained decline are much more real.
If house prices are lower and a credit crunch pushes America into recession, the industry undoubtedly faces a harsher future.
We need to keep an eye on those dorsal fins.
British bankers found guilty in Enron case
Three British bankers who went on trial for their role in the fraud with former Enron chief financial officer Andrew Fastow were found guilty on Wednesday.
David Bermingham, Giles Darby and Gary Mulgrew were originally found not guilty of seven counts of fraud for colluding with Fastow in a secret financial operation in 2000 to enrich themselves at the expense of employees.
They were sent to trial in January.
But during the hearing before U.S. District Judge Ewing Werlein Jr., each was convicted of conspiracy to commit fraud.
The three former executives of Greenwich Natwest, a unit of the Scottish PLC group at Royal Bank, became a celebrity cause in Britain over extradition proceedings that lasted two years.
In the United States, his case marks the loose end of an investigation launched after the collapse of Enron in 2001.
Initially, the charges against the bankers were for alerting Fastow in 2002 that he was the target of a government investigation into the collapse of Enron.
The indictment against the bankers - dubbed the "NatWest Three" - alleges they came to Houston in 2000 to fabricate a fraudulent scheme with Fastow and his former top aide, Michael Kopper.
Greenwich Natwest had invested in a subsidiary of an Enron corporation controlled by Fastow, who was the mastermind behind a myriad of scams at Enron, which helped spiral it into bankruptcy.
In 2002, the bank valued the subsidiary's interest at zero, but the three Britons knew it would rise.
A company under Kopper's control bought the bank interest in the subsidiary for $1 million.
The bankers paid Kopper $250,000 for interest in that company.
According to the indictment, Fastow falsely represented Enron, as the energy company would pay Greenwich NatWest $20 million for its shares in the subsidiary.
But the 20 million went to the British bankers, Fastow and others.
The bankers took in $7.3 million, while Fastow, Kopper and others received about $12.3 million, according to the indictment.
In January 2004, Fastow was found guilty on two counts of conspiracy to cause the collapse of Enron.
The British trio was arrested three months later.
Fastow is serving a six-year sentence at a federal prison in Louisiana.
Kopper is serving a three-year, one-month sentence in Texarkana.
Each of the three British bankers must pay $1 million they required to live in the United States while the trial was held.
Enron, one of the nation's seven largest companies, declared bankrupt in December 2001 after years of accounting tricks, could not hide millions in debt or make its failing businesses look successful.
The collapse caused thousands of jobs to be lost, more than $60 million in market equities and more than $2 million in pension plans.
Enron founder Kenneth Lay and former CEO Jeffrey Skilling were convicted last year for their roles in the company's collapse.
Skilling is serving a sentence of more than 24 years.
Lay's conviction on conspiracy, fraud and other charges was stayed when he died of a heart attack last year.
Neither down nor out in Moscow
The price of a Gulfstream G550 aircraft, equipped with a Rolls-Royce engine and enough fuel capacity to fly direct from Moscow to Los Angeles, starts at $54 million.
But this is a small expense for some of the rich Russians.
"It can carry up to 18 passengers", says Dan Firer, a Gulfstream representative.
"But nobody asks for that model with so many seats because it's for private family flights or for company presidents".
Mr. Firer was in charge of the Gulfstream booth last Friday at the Millionaire's Fair, a four-day consumer orgy held at an event center outside the capital.
In addition to Gulfstream, 200 other luxury suppliers had set up their booths, hoping to lure the newly wealthy Russians to all kinds of products, from mahogany-armored yachts to 50-cent diamond-encrusted car grills.
Mr. Firer looks cautiously at a bright orange Porsche in the booth next to his".
"It's a beautiful car, but it's nickel and brass compared to us", he said.
"After the United States, Russia is the second largest market for private jets".
Fueled by the oil boom, the Russian capital looks like Dallas when it was at its peak.
"We had the same thing in 1890 when some wealthy Americans came to Europe to meet, where they were seen as materialistic", says Marshall Goldman, senior professor at Harvard University's Davis Center for Russian and Eurasian Studies.
"Like the Saudis in the 1970s and the Japanese in the 1990s, the Russians are emerging as the world's biggest consumers and spenders".
The world's most exclusive luxury brands are looking for their share of the pie.
Elsewhere in Moscow, a conference on the luxury industry will be held this week with Donatella Versace, Tom Ford and Bernard Arnault, the chairman of LVMH, to exchange ideas on how to sell luxury goods in markets such as Russia.
(The conference is organized by the International Herald Tribune, owned by the New York Times Company)
Russia has 53 billionaires making a total of $282 billion dollars, according to Forbes' list of richest people.
In addition, the second-rich include 103,000 Russian billionaires whose wealth reaches $670 billion, according to a study of personal wealth trends in the former Soviet Union, written by economists at the Center for Economic and Financial Research, a local think tank.
(The World Bank says that in 2005, 15.8% of Russians were living below the subsistence level.)
"There are hundreds of millionaires in Moscow - and that's why we're all here", says Nicole Marais, sales and marketing representative for London jeweler David Morris.
She attends the fair for the first time alongside the brand's Russian distributor, the Soho Jewelry group.
"The women are impeccably dressed and the men are very dignified".
Visiting the fair on Sunday night, dressed in evening gowns, two real estate agents, Evgenia Yumatova, 21, and Svetlana Turovtsova, 26, described their clients and themselves as millionaires.
"I was looking at the cars and I'm trying to decide between the Infiniti, the Mercedes and the Porsche", said Yumatova, who reeled off the designer suit she wore as a veteran red carpet dishing with Joan Rivers.
The fair aims to attract the new rich, the kind of shoppers who would be willing to stay for several hours in a warehouse that mixes brands from Cadillac Escalades, platinum fountain pens, Mövenpick ice cream, bespoke pool tables, apartments in Dubai and Gund teddy bears.
The general public can buy tickets for 30 euros ($44.57 USD).
"The Russians are interested in learning which brand is the most expensive and the best", said Mr. Gijrath, who sat patriotically at a stand of Delft's Royal Dutch Porcelain in front of a mural-sized reconstruction of a Rembrandt painting, made of hand-painted tiles.
"Of course, the Russians are more interested in the bling-bling.
In fact, sellers said that wealthy older Russians (10 to 15 years, by Russian standards) have changed their tastes from flashy logos to limited edition brands, which would not be exhibited at a trade show.
Yet, several thousand people - cash millionaires, emissaries of millionaires or tourists - fill the halls every day.
And some of them buy.
On the first night of the fair last Thursday, Roman Ershov, general manager of King Koil beds, said he sold two mattress systems for $70,000 each, made of silk, cashmere and cotton woven with gold threads.
Also on the first night, Mikhail Lyubiumov, sales manager for A1 Moto, a company that equips high-end cars with ad hoc alarm systems, said the company had sold the bright orange Porsche, for $170,000 dollars to a Russian millionaire.
On Sunday afternoon, Andrei Karapetian, president of L.A. Connection, a company that modifies luxury cars for particular requirements, said he had sold three car grilles shaped like chain bracelets, for Rolls Royce Phantom, for $55,000 each.
He showed the reporter a car wheel, designed for the owner of a Russian casino, with rays embedded in Swarovski-colored crystals, so that it resembled a roulette wheel.
Cost: $22,000 for four wheels.
"The Russian millionaire who wants ostrich leather wheels or a portrait of his wife made of zirconia cubes, is not necessarily going to drive on those wheels", says Mr. Karapetian.
"He's going to keep the car in his garage, along with 30 or 40 other cars".
Even if many of his Russian clients are wealthy, Mr. Karapetian makes it clear that the phrase "Russian millionaire" does not mean exclusivity, given the surge in real estate prices.
"If you bought an apartment in Moscow three or four years ago, you're probably already a millionaire, at least on paper if not in cash", he said.
"There are more of them than you think".
Those who were not millionaires could at least pretend to be rich with the support of the Continental Alliance, a Russian asset management firm.
The company made four red (British style) telephone booths filled with piles of fake one million dollar bills.
Azad Karryev, the company's marketing manager, said his team had printed 500,000 fake bills for the Millionaire's Fair.
Visitors would stop to shake piles of money, asking their friends to take pictures with their phones while resting on piles of money, or pocketing a couple of million.
"You see, in Moscow, everyone can feel like a millionaire", says Karryev.
"Snap" surgery could be a cause of death in New Jersey
It was the day before Thanksgiving when Ronald Livingston looked out the window of the A Little Healthier restaurant and saw an ambulance coming up White Cape Cod, two doors down on West Scott Avenue.
Suddenly, a police car showed up.
And then another one.
"Then I saw the ambulance come up", said Mr. Livingston, the restaurant supervisor, that Wednesday.
"That's when I knew someone had died".
Authorities have learned that the dead woman is Olga Arroyo, 41, assistant director of the Newark Police Department.
Now investigators are trying to determine if she died due to a procedure performed by an unauthorized plastic surgeon, who is not yet identified by police, but who works at the 212 West Scott Ave. home.
Authorities have yet to determine the cause of Ms. Arroyo's death, but they're waiting for the tox screen, although the results won't be available for a few weeks, which will help solve the mysterious death that has plagued the Newark police force's senior ranks.
Mrs. Arroyo had been assistant to the chief of police, Garry F. McCarthy, since September 2006, and her voice was familiar to many in the department.
"She was loyal, hardworking and tenacious", Mr. McCarthy says of Arroyo in a telephone interview Wednesday.
"She was my guardian".
She was protecting me".
Mr. McCarthy said Arroyo was the wife of Jimmy Arroyo, a former Newark police officer who works for the Liquor Control Commission, and that she left behind two sons, ages 14 and 11, and a stepdaughter.
Eileen Walsh, spokeswoman for Union County Prosecutor Theodore J. Romankow, said detectives are trying to determine if Mrs. Arroyo died as a result of an unauthorized surgical procedure.
"That's one possibility", Walsh declared.
"It's an ongoing investigation".
Authorities said they arrived at the house around 3 p.m.
November 21st and they found Mrs. Arroyo on a couch.
She was pronounced dead at the scene.
It's been over a week and authorities have said little about their investigation or the owner of the house, named Flor Margarita Castro.
Mrs. Walsh couldn't say if Mrs. Castro has been questioned by the authorities.
Investigators are trying to determine what part of the house was used as a medical practice.
On Wednesday, no one answered the door at Mrs. Castro's home, where a withered rose bush is located in the front of the house, and a barking dalmatian in the back.
A blue drum labeled "vanillin ethyl" - used as a substitute for vanilla in food and perfumes - was located on the garage door, next to a door leading to the basement.
Two mountain bikes hanging on hooks on one side.
Mr. McCarthy said that when she arrived in Newark after 25 years in the NYPD, Mrs. Arroyo was an invaluable help in getting to know the new island city and its rough political culture.
"She would say, 'You have to watch out with this or that,'" she said.
"She was always here when I was, and also when I wasn't.
It's embarrassing".
The Fed is expected to cut rates to lift the stock market.
Stocks jumped on both sides of the Atlantic yesterday after the market expected the Federal Reserve to ease credit conditions with interest rate cuts, which were heightened by reassuring comments from the vice chairman of the U.S. central bank.
Stock markets loosened in London, New York and across Europe after Donald Kohn, number two to Ben Bernanke, the chairman of the Federal Reserve, declared that policymakers must be "flexible and pragmatic" in responding to continued financial market stress.
In a clear effort to reassure markets amid growing credit-exchange samples, Mr Kohn said the recent turmoil was "partly reversed by the improvement in the market in late September and during October".
If the upward trend persists, it would increase the possibility of further adjustments in financial conditions for real estate and business, Kohn said.
The comments were taken by investors as a sign that the reserve is ready to inject fresh capital into US markets and to make further interest rate cuts to stabilize credit conditions.
The remarks also helped to calm Wall Street amid bad news for the US economy, such as home sales hitting a record low in October.
The fallout from the financial turmoil was accentuated by an announcement by Bear Stearns, an investment bank that will cut 650 jobs, equivalent to 4% of its total workforce, in an overall cost cut to offset losses on its U.S. sub-prime mortgage investments.
Only 20 of those positions are expected to come to London, where the bank employs 1,500 people.
In New York, the Dow Jones industrial average rose 331 points, or 2.55%, at close to 13,289.40, while the broad S&P 500 index rose 2.65%.
In London, the FTSE 100 index rose 165.5 points, or 2.7%, at close to 6,306.2, adding more than £39 billion to the value of Britain's top companies.
Germany's Dax index rose by 2.6%, and France's CAC40 was above 2.3%.
Earlier, the re-emergence of credit stress on the markets was highlighted following strong demand at a three-month auction of funds by the European Central Bank, which valued these loans to European commercial banks at 4.7%, the highest rate since April 2001.
Pressure on the Bank of England to follow the lead of the Federal Reserve and the ECB and to inject extra funds into the London stock markets, strained credit and three-month LIBOR lending rates among British banks, which meant the biggest rise since September, at 6.59%, after a steady rise since 12 November.
England takes Owais Shah and Ravi Bopara's demands to court
Here are two dilemmas, each as difficult as the other.
Who should beat England's No. 6 in Kandy this weekend, Owais Shah or Ravi Bopara?
And none of them are less important than the first Test against Sri Lanka, who should make the decision?
The second question is relevant because David Graveney, the chairman of the national team who is on loan - with that particular title at least - is here to help Peter Moores, the coach, and Michael Vaughan, the captain, decide; and also because the desk of Hugh Morris, England manager, is starting to fill with offers to become a national selector, and if not, a part-time one.
Whoever doesn't get the sixth batting title will be unlucky, but life is often unfair and so is sport.
It is not easy to throw what one man does at the top of his profession, while another never goes beyond the bottom level, sometimes out of bad luck rather than ability.
It's not just in cricket that choice is difficult, as it requires judgments that always end up being subjective.
Is it just the right time for Bopara to get up?
Is it fair for Shah if he does it?
The same question could be asked in another aspect if, says John Edwards or "Tubby" Banerjee, two brilliant young executives with good degrees and who know the business well, were promoted to the board: there is only room for one of them.
Who's to say what a good level is for a cricketer, unless they give him the chance to sink or swim at the next chance?
Figures naturally have a big influence on decisions, but so do opportunities.
Within a team, a cricketer has to catch the eye of the captain at the same time as taking a wicket and a batsman to get chances to change the order if he wants to make an impact as a player someday.
But catching the eye of the coaches is more complicated.
There were many who improved last season, for example, James Anderson, who is certainly playing in the first Test even if Stephen Harmison declares for fit and bowls like the wind in the nets.
Anderson took 32 first-class wickets in 33 runs for each to earn a place.
Chris Tremlett took only 29 on the same average, but they both had their high times and can expect more of these.
Shah or Bopara games at the Asgiriya stadium can only be a matter of opinion.
The choice can break or make a man's career, or it can mean a small difference.
Four years ago in Sri Lanka, Gareth Batty played every Test and did well in the first one, with 5 wickets and 40 runs, but it was Paul Collingwood, struggling to establish himself at the same time who came to become a key player, and despite scoring a double century against Australia in Australia, he may still be underrated.
Chances are Graveney, Vaughan and Moores, after a further discussion in today's session at Asgiriya Stadium, will follow their conservation instincts and favor Shah's greater experience over the exuberance of young Bopara.
There are arguments for both.
In Shah's favour is his brilliant and valuable Test debut early in '88 in Mumbai, 32 first-class centuries versus only 6 from Bopara, who, at 22, is seven years younger, and has an excellent record against spin bowling.
But Shah made only ten runs in his two innings in May against West Indies in the Test at Lord's, his home ground as a Middlesex player, and that caused an immediate rejection from the selectors when Vaughan claimed his place for the next match, he seemed to have taken from his batting some of the momentum that he had in Mumbai.
On the contrary, the Essex team is happy to live on swords.
He gets caught up in everything on the cricket field and his attitude was summed up as when he overturned his car at an exhibition for the UK car sponsor, Volkswagen.
He suffered minor injuries and presumably shock, but the first thing he did was to pull out his Vodafone (sponsored, of course) and call Alastair Cook, his teammate who was looking in the distance, to say excitedly, "Did you see that?"
Bopara is the best player, he's including his slippery pass to have effects on his plays that seem to satisfy him, as he bats with confidence and skill.
Picking the right man is one thing, picking the right time is another.
Maybe that's the real art of selecting.
My inclination would be to give Bopara his chance, which doesn't mean Shah doesn't stand out, as the tea leaves suggest, he's the one playing here this weekend.
Buses bring refugees back to work - and fight Al-Qaeda
The first buses carrying Iraqi refugees from Syria began arriving in Baghdad yesterday, expelling exiles who ran out of cash, visa extensions and were waiting for the city to return to normal.
Some had even returned to fight the militants who drove them from their homes.
At the Mansour bus station, even before 800 people arrived from Damascus in an official government convoy of a dozen buses, the terminal was filled with refugees from Syria and Jordan who had returned by private transport.
"I decided to go to Syria after many doctors were killed in Baghdad", says Sabah al-Qubaisi, a Sunni doctor.
"I came back today because of what I saw on TV and what I read in the newspapers, about what happened in Baghdad and that it's safe now".
"They say the army of the Mahdi stopped killing people", he says, referring to the Shiite militia of religious militant Cleric Moqtada al-Sadr, who ordered his troops to cease momentarily.
Qassim al-Atwani, a 38-year-old Shiite teacher in the Sunni Amariyah area, returned with his two children because it was impossible to renew his visa in Syria because the regime does not want Iraqis working in their country.
His Shiite neighbors in Amariyah phoned him to tell him that an allied US force had helped push Al-Qaeda out of their stronghold west of the capital, and urged him to return.
One of the newcomers from Jordan was the chief of a Sunni and Shiite tribe who had been driven from his home in Sleikh north of Baghdad by a grenade attack after he urged citizens to rise up against Al-Qaeda.
He had come to fight.
"Two days ago, some of my friends called me and told me that they had started an anti-Al-Qaeda militia in Sleikh and that they needed my support and that of my colleagues".
"That is why I have returned today", said Sabaah Alu Obeidi, 62.
Many said they were attracted by the growing calm in the capital since US troops have entrenched groups of "concerned citizens", armed and working in cooperation with the US military to defend their neighborhoods.
But many said they returned because of visa denial and lack of money in Damascus, where more than 1.3 million Iraqis have settled in recent years.
Salaam al-Samarrai, 51, a father of three, voiced a common suspicion among the exiles, that Nouri al-Maliki, the Shiite prime minister, asked the Syrian government to impose restrictions on refugee visas to force people to return.
More than two and a half million people are believed to have fled the country because of sectarian death gangs.
"We were fine until al-Maliki visited Syria and urged the government to stop issuing visas to Iraqis, to force them to return to Iraq", the Sunni said.
"I can't believe a government supports criminals who burned my house down after I left".
Part of the reason for the cessation of violence is that the Sunnis have been driven out of the Shiite areas and vice versa, easing tensions.
There is a fear that a sudden wave of refugees will reignite sectarian tensions and start fighting.
The little Saar, good education.
The smallest federal state is the first in vocational training and even shines by the international orientation of its higher education institutions.
As in the whole country, the Saarlanders lack only an educational field.
"Yesterday I explained for the 50th time to a non-Sarlandese that we are not French" - that was the ironic motto about themselves of the smallest federal state for its 50th anniversary.
At the same time France and Luxembourg play a major role in the education system in the Saarland, which in a study by the German Institute of Economics (IW) called "Bildungsmonitor" was ranked fifth.
Thus, higher education institutions have traditionally enjoyed good relations with neighbouring countries.
The University of Saarbrücken was founded in 1948 by the French.
Even today students can finish their university career here with two or three diplomas.
Consequently, the percentage of foreign students is high, at 15.6 percent.
However, the number of students from the Saarland is higher than the average in the upper secondary schools.
"The Saarland takes advantage of the vocational education system", says Axel Plünnecke, the education expert at the Institute of German Economics (IW).
More than one in five young people finish their secondary education at a vocational school, which means that the Saarland is 7 percentage points above the national average.
The range of possibilities for vocational education and training is very wide.
The offer of dual careers, in relation to the number of inhabitants, is the second best in Germany.
Despite practical vocational training and growing demand, the number of graduates in Engineering Science has fallen by a third in recent years.
This was the reason why the Saarland Ministry of Education forced the higher education institutions to advertise more for engineering specialties.
"After the first PISA study, we have made some reforms in general education schools", says a spokeswoman for the Ministry of Education.
So the government introduced comparative testing nationwide.
In order to get the children to start their final year of study as soon as possible, the project called "Kita-Jahr" is free of charge.
Comparison with future studies will show whether it has increased pupil performance.
According to the 2003 PISA report, the number of students with school-leaving backwardness decreased from 29 percent to 20 percent.
But overall, the Saarland did not improve much like other federal states.
In Bavaria, students are better at calculating.
To the dismay of the Saarlanders, the PISA report does not compare foreign language skills, although in this field they could achieve good results.
Although the Sarlans are not French, the language of the neighbours is a compulsory subject in secondary schools.
Chavez is changing the time.
Soon in Venezuela there will be another time zone different from the rest of the world.
On December 9, President Hugo Chávez changes the time in the South American country by moving the clock back half an hour.
Currently Chavez is staying as a comedian in Spain.
As reported in the Official State Bulletin, according to the new law, the time will be minus four hours GMT.
This will give the South American country a time zone that does not exist in any other country in the world.
Among other things, Chavez, as an enemy of the United States, justifies his decision by saying that the United States would impose the obligation on the world by changing a full hour.
In addition, on Wednesday (local time) Chávez announced the breakdown of relations with his neighboring country Colombia because of the hostage-taking action.
The left-wing nationalist said he would not maintain any relationship with either the head of state or the Colombian government until conservative Álvaro Uribe remains president of Colombia.
"My dignity does not allow me to do it", says Chávez, who is pushing for a constitutional reform where the citizens of the oil-rich country must decide on Sunday in a referendum.
With this reform, his power in the country could be greatly expanded.
The reason for the conflict was the decision taken by Uribe to withdraw Chávez's mandate in negotiations with the Marxist guerrillas in which it was about the release of the hostages.
On Sunday, Chávez said that Uribe's decision offended Venezuela.
In Spain too, much is said about Chávez.
A new call tone is causing a sensation in the country: "Why don't you shut up?", is the phrase that has already been downloaded by half a million people.
This phrase was uttered by the King of Spain who was upset by the continuous interruptions by left-wing populists at the last Ibero-American Summit.
In 2007 the decline in real wages threatens the Germans.
According to one forecast, a fall in real wages threatens German employees this year despite a strong economic situation.
Experts present a host of reasons for a pessimistic forecast.
According to the calculations of the Hans Böckler Foundation, German employees should have a lower real wage bill in 2007 than in the previous year.
"The blame for this lies in the weak wage developments, the rise in value added tax and the tightening of food and energy prices", reports Gustav Horn of the Institute for Macroeconomics and Business Cycles Research in the newspaper "Bild".
New unemployment insurance charges may also be imposed on employees.
The Minister of Finance Peter Setinbrück told the newspaper "Neue Ostanbrücker Zeitung" that given the current situation, the intention to reduce the unemployment insurance burden by 3.3% from one year to the next is just and reasonable.
The employment office, of course, does not have to get into a bad situation again by asking the Federal State for loans and subsidies, as one German Social Democrat politician put it.
On Tuesday, it was made public that the rate of inflation with the explosion in prices in the food sector and the oil derivatives sector reached the highest level in 13 years.
Compared with last year, prices are up 3%.
Venus: twin brother of Earth.
Despite its atmosphere not being suitable for life, Venus is the planet most similar to Earth, something that had not been considered until now.
For three decades, researchers had suspected that lightning might exist on Venus.
But now the European probe has brought new evidence: it has discovered electromagnetic waves at the edge of the atmosphere. On Venus, lightning strikes from a height of 34 miles [54 km] from one cloud to another, says Cris Russell of the University of California at Los Angeles to the scientific journal Nature.
According to the famous Urey-Miller model of the origin of life, lightning caused life on Earth: storms could have caused reactions in the ocean that, in turn, would have given rise to the amino acids that are the basic components of life.
Venus is not like that: if life ever existed there, it would have to be in one of the earliest stages of evolution", explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution in Washington.
Today, there can be no life on the surface of Venus: the atmospheric pressure is almost 100 times higher than on Earth and the surface temperatures are 500°C, fluctuating in such a way that temperatures can reach below zero.
"Venus may be a 'devil' twin of Earth, but it's still a twin", Russell said.
The main objective of the "Venus Express" mission is to answer the question of why Venus, so similar to Earth in its mass and size, has had such a different evolution.
Since since the 1990s there were no special missions, only for research of this planet, the launch of "Venus-Express" in November 2005 was a very important step for the research of Venus.
The latest results of the research, which will be presented in many articles in Nature, underline, in the opinion of the researchers, not only the uniqueness of Venus in the Solar System.
"This also shows that the neighboring planets have more features in common with Earth than we had assumed", reports ESA.
Despite the already known stormy winds at the North Pole, researchers also discovered a faster-spinning cloud vortex in the south polar region.
This phenomenon is reminiscent of wind flows in the upper atmospheric layers of the Earth's poles, as described by a team of researchers led by Giuseppe Piccioni of the Italian Institute of Special Astrophysics and Space Physics.
The second planet in the Solar System has a mass almost equal to that of the Earth and is almost as large at its equatorial diameter of 12,000 kilometers.
This planet, also called the morning star or evening star, orbits the Sun for nearly 225 days.
But its rotation period is slower: a day on Venus is equivalent to 243 days on Earth.
Although Venus, with its surface temperatures of 1,300 degrees Fahrenheit [4,660°C] and atmospheric pressure of 92 bar, bears little resemblance to Earth, scientists assume that both planets formed under similar conditions.
On both planets, water had clumped up, which on Earth remained in the oceans, but on Venus it dissociated into the universe.
While on Earth carbon dioxide had turned into carbon stones, on Venus it forms most of the atmosphere.
