Richard Gere is just missing more cynicism.
The two films "The Hunting Party" and "Moerderischer Frieden" are again devoted to the war in the Balkans.
But neither of them had much conviction.
Either the concepts are too focused on action and gunfights or the two movies are too exciting.
Richard Gere with his "The Hunting Party" can't help in this case either.
At first there was good news: Karadzic and Mladic, the war criminals, are still hiding in the Balkan mountains, but it was there, in the dark interior of the country during the Bosnian war, that actor Richard Gere was rediscovered.
We had finally lost sight of the handsomest man of the 1980s, because no one wanted to see him after his pleasant, low-profile roles in women's movies and after many press conferences about Buddhism.
Now, suddenly, Richard Gere is the most important argument for maybe watching the movie "The Hunting Party - when a hunter becomes what he chases" (Why do movie titles have to be so long and silly nowadays?).
The film has a wonderful presentation for the viewer: at bottom, his role as a war reporter is a presentation of what Richard Gere could have done, if fate and the film industry had not been so merciful to him.
"The Hunting Party", despite this triumph, along with "Moerderischer Frieden" which is a German production and will also be released this week, turn out to be just a series of unsuccessful films about the war in the Balkans.
The film "Moerderischer Frieden" can be narrated in a few words: it is about two German soldiers in Kosovo (Adrian Topol, Max Riemelt) who want to save a Serbian woman from Kosovo snipers, one of them acts very quickly and that also leads him to fall in love with her.
The film's meaning is lost to the actions and the shootings, although we celebrate that the Serbs are not once again being presented as the only culprits.
The movie is like the German series "Alarm for Cobra 11" without a highway, but in a war situation.
In the example of "The Hunting Party" you can investigate, because there was never really a good movie about the war in the Balkans.
At another time, with another director and another screenwriter (Richard Shepard on two occasions), the story about American reporters in the war who go to track down a Serbian war criminal called "fox", could probably be a new "Apocalypse Now".
So the stories are surprisingly similar: small teams go to the mountains twice to do something the army can't do, and each time it's a crazy trip.
One reason for the failure of "The Hunting Party" is that we are introduced to Simon Hunt at the beginning, who is not allowed to be simply a cynic with a heart.
No, the script also foresees a love affair with a Bosnian Muslim woman who they're going to kill later.
So "The Hunting Party" is far from reality, especially when in the last five minutes the reporters with impressive speed accomplish what NATO, CIA and all the headhunters in the world failed to do for five years, which was to capture the war criminal and leave it to the Bosnian Muslims to exact their fair revenge.
It's so bad, they want to appeal to the international court in The Hague based on crimes against cinematic logic.
However, the purpose of the film is, in fact, a deeply human one.
The film wants to condemn the fact that Karadzic and Mladic are still free, and highlights that the Americans and French are not really concerned about prosecuting them, because they have political arrangements between them.
Sometimes good and bad are so similar, you'll think of a very famous Brecht poem.
In this poem it is a mask of an Asian demon: "In the great wrinkles of his forehead I see, sharing the feelings with him, how hard it is to be bad".
In movies like "The Hunting Party" there are also these demons but they prove how hard it is to be good.
The problem is not just the genre of war films in the Balkans.
He recently published in a newspaper that all the films about Iraq produced in Hollywood are fiascos.
It may also be added that there has never been a good film about South Africa.
One rule almost always applies: when a star gets into a crisis region or into minefields, then something like "Rangoon" with Patricia Arguette, "Over All Borders" with Angelina Jolie or "Bloody Diamonds" with Leonardo DiCaprio pops up.
Possibly all these conflicts occurred in a short space of time.
It's got to be at least decades before Hollywood rolls out a good Holocaust movie, like Schindler's List.
Some films need more time, and classics like the Vietnam War movies "The Deer Hunter", "Apocalypse Now", or "Full Metal Jackett" were not universally hailed as masterpieces in their day.
Today we may know too much about world conflicts, and that is why in our times every massacre (Massenmord) is shown live on two television sets at home.
And that's because screenwriters don't have the slightest qualms (that are necessary to be able to) to tell good stories.
"To be or not to be" or "The Great Dictator" turned out to be so good in the end, because Lubitsch and Chaplin still didn't know how bad the Nazi regime really was.
Maybe you don't have to be a good person to make a movie.
Maybe we should be like the novelist Lawrence Norfolk, with his sarcastic, distant look of an artist.
When asked about the parallels between his historical novel "Lemprière's Dictionary" and the war in the Balkans, he replied: "That's only because some things never change".
The big cities will always be in danger, men will always be cruelly killed and war will always reign in Yugoslavia.
