It's not the wooden boxes.
If you think of Sweden and a wooden box, you think of Ikea, but you don't think of Andy Warhol.
Or is it?
Today, wooden boxes produced in Sweden are like a shadow that weighs on the list of Warhol's works.
Most of the 94 "type" Glow-Box on this list are fakes.
After the Swedish newspaper Expressen questioned the authenticity of Andy Warhol's 1968 Brillo-Boxes a few months ago, the Moderna Museet in Stockholm conducted internal investigations and came to disappointing conclusions: the six Brillo-Boxes, which the former director of the museum Pontus Hultén gave to Moderna Museet, are fake, and almost a hundred of the other "Stockholm-type" ones, which are in circulation on the international art market, are also.
Prehistory is too complicated with a confused relationship between artistic and sponsored productions.
In 1964 Warhol created his first "Brillo-Boxes" in New York, painting the wooden boxes red, blue and white, with the same sample that had "Brillo" soap powder cartons.
According to Warhol, in the 1968 exhibition of his works at the Moderna Museet, hundreds of Brillo-cardboard boxes were on display.
These were not works of art, but copies (which were only objects) on display.
In the same year, 1968, Warhol was allowed to produce in Sweden some wooden Shine-boxes, but they were not exhibited in the Modern Museet museum.
Witnesses of those times now speak of almost fifteen boxes, which at that time entered the history of art and auctions as original "Stockholm-type" "Brillo-Boxes" authorized by Andy Warhol.
Some of them were sold at auction for over $100,000.
The problem is that after the famous museum director Pontus Hultén made false statements that in 1968 in Sweden were produced and exhibited almost a hundred of the wooden boxes that Warhol left him.
But in reality, 105 boxes were produced in the same year 1990 in Malmö for Hultén and for the exhibition in St. Petersburg.
By this time Warhol had been dead for three years.
Lars Byström, the head of the museum's conservators at Moderna Museet, investigated six Museum-owned Brillo-Boxes and also three Swedish private-owned ones that were manufactured in 1968 in Stockholm.
On the contrary, the structure of the 1990 copies shows that the paint was applied with a roller without directly printing the tight plates.
"These boxes have not been authorized by the artist and should be removed from the official list of Andy Warhol's Shine-Boxes", says Lars Nittve, the director of the Moderna Museet, adding that if the "Andy Warhol Art" Authentication Commission in New York fails to reach a conclusion, the Moderna Museet will classify these six boxes as copies/exhibits.
Already in July the Commission of Authentication formally announced that it accepted these "serious allegations" that they were boxes of soap dust.
But from that moment on, everything was silent.
